Citations
Date:  0/0/1906
Source:  Plants of NZ
Author:  LAING & BLACKWELL
Vol / Page:  64
Edition:  1940
Quote:  If far from water, the carriage [of kauri logs] is more difficult. A skidded road, six to eight feet wide, is formed of greased logs. Thus a sort of rough wooden tramway is made. The logs are hoisted onto this road by means of `jacks', or dragged by a team of bullocks.
